ordpress-hacks/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:60:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/3-common-wordpress-hacks/#respond";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Tue, 12 Apr 2016 04:21:54 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Our Blog";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:33:"http://mylocalwebstop.com/?p=2449";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:378:"<p>By learning what techniques hackers use to hack our sites, we can learn how to prevent these types of hacks and better secure our WordPress sites.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/3-common-wordpress-hacks/">The 3 Most Common WordPress Hacks</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"Frank";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5581:"<p><em>This content of this post was originally posted on my personal blog. <a href="http://frankcorso.me/3-most-common-wordpress-hacks/" target="_blank">Click here to view the original article.</a></em></p>\n<p>When it comes to our websites, we know security is a big deal. However, we don&#8217;t always know how the hackers will attack your site. Most attacks are very similar which allows us to see the most common approaches. By knowing what the hackers will most likely try, we can secure our site to prevent those attacks. So, here are the three most common hack techniques used when attacking WordPress sites.</p>\n<h3>Brute Force Attack</h3>\n<p>A brute force attack is one of the most common attacks on any site. In this attack, the hacker is guessing your password over and over until he figures out your password. Of course, the hacker is no longer doing this manually. He has several scripts running at the same time that is trying to figure out passwords to many sites at the same time. One form of the brute force attack is called a dictionary attack. This is where the hacker uses every word in a dictionary as the password. Since several of the most common passwords are single words, the dictionary attack is a quick attack to gain access to your site.</p>\n<p>So, how do you protect your site from a brute force attack? The first step is to ensure your passwords are secure. A few simple best practices includes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Do not use words in your password</li>\n<li>Do not use short passwords</li>\n<li>Use multiple types of characters</li>\n<li>Change passwords regularly</li>\n<li>Do not give your password out</li>\n<li>Use different passwords for each site and service</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Next, you want to make sure the hacker can&#8217;t even find a username to try. So, make sure there is no user with a common username such as admin, administrator, or developer. Most security plugins have many features in place to prevent a brute force attack. A common method is to prevent the amount of tries a user has to log in. If your password is not strong, the hacker&#8217;s script can usually figure out your password in 15,000 tries which takes less than a few seconds. So, if you limit the amount of guesses to 3 or 5, that stops the script from even being able to make its guesses.</p>\n<h3>SQL Injection Hacks</h3>\n<p>Lets assume that you have an unsecure search form on your site. A normal visitor can type in what they want to look for. Then the site will retrieve the data from the database and display the data to the user. Now, if a hacker was using the form, he would type in certain words and symbols that would change what data the site is retrieving. Instead of showing a list of posts, the hacker would make the form show him a list of posts and list of all usernames and passwords. This is sql injection. SQL Injection is when a hacker enters malicious words and characters into a form that is unsecure to exploit the database in some way. Depending on the site, a hacker could use sql injection to retrieve usernames and passwords, retrieve credit card numbers, alter data, or even delete data.</p>\n<p>How do you protect your site against SQL Injection hacks? If you&#8217;re the developer, you would follow <a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Validating_Sanitizing_and_Escaping_User_Data">WordPress sanitizing, escaping, and validation functions and techniques</a>. However, most people are not developers. So, we need to find quality plugins that we know are secure and do not install plugins from untrusted sources or developers. When installing a plugin, check the plugin&#8217;s reviews and support forums for any indication that it may not be secure.</p>\n<h3>Cross Site Scripting</h3>\n<p>Cross Site Scripting, or XSS for short, is when a hacker adds his malicious script to your site. For example, if the hacker finds a way to embed his tracking script into your theme, he will be able to track all of your websites visitors. This is a basic example of Cross Site Scripting. Another example that I have seen recently is when a website had a form where visitors could enter testimonials. The entered testimonials are then displayed across the entire website. The hacker entered in some malicious code into the form which then added his script to every page on the site. Now, every time a visitor visited the website, they were redirected to a different website claiming that their computer was now infected and they needed to pay $99 to fix it.</p>\n<p>Protecting your site from Cross Site Scripting hacks is crucial to ensure no visitor can embed their scripts into your site. Again, always install plugins from trusted sources such as <a href="https://wordpress.org/">wordpress.org</a> and from trusted developers.</p>\n<p>Now that you know the basic concepts of the most common hacks, be sure to always discuss these with any plugin developer, theme developer, or any other developer that you have working on your site. To learn more about WordPress security, consider<a href="http://mylocalwebstop.com/sign-up-for-our-free-security-course/" target="_blank"> registering for our free WordPress Security 101 email course.</a></p>\n<p>Has your site ever been hacked? Do you know how the hackers attacked your site? Be sure to comment below about the hacks that you have encountered so that we can all learn from them.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/3-common-wordpress-hacks/">The 3 Most Common WordPress Hacks</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:57:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/3-common-wordpress-hacks/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:42:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:26:"Keep your software updated";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:54:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/keep-your-software-updated/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:62:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/keep-your-software-updated/#respond";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 28 Jan 2016 20:51:26 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Our Blog";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:33:"http://mylocalwebstop.com/?p=2421";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:542:"<p>When it comes to our websites, we know security is a big deal. The most common types of hacks on WordPress sites include SQL Injection and Cross Site Scripting. However, most users are not developers who would know what these are and what to look for in their plugins and themes in order to prevent these [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/keep-your-software-updated/">Keep your software updated</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"Frank";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3081:"<p>When it comes to our websites, we know security is a big deal. The most common types of hacks on WordPress sites include SQL Injection and Cross Site Scripting. However, most users are not developers who would know what these are and what to look for in their plugins and themes in order to prevent these hacks. Luckily, as security vulnerabilities are found, most developers respond quickly to fix the issue and release the patch as an update. However, many users do not update their software regularly. While maintaining your site, there are several things that you want to keep updated.</p>\n<h2>WordPress</h2>\n<p>The very first software that you need to ensure is always up-to-date is WordPress itself. There are usually less than 6 updates all year. The updates are usually well tested among dozens, if not hundreds, of developers and users. Since WordPress powers 25% of the internet, if a security vulnerability becomes known, hackers immediately start trying to hack sites using that vulnerability. That is why it is crucial to always keep WordPress updated.</p>\n<h2>WordPress Plugins and Themes</h2>\n<p>The biggest risk of security vulnerability usually comes from WordPress plugins and themes because most sites have dozens of different kinds made by dozens of different developers. So, it is quite possible to have 2 security patch updates in a single week on your site. So, if you only update your plugins and themes once every month or so, you are leaving your site vulnerable to the hackers who become aware of the security vulnerabilities in plugins and themes.</p>\n<h2>Server&#8217;s PHP</h2>\n<p>PHP is the programming language that is run on your hosting server that runs WordPress. Programming languages can also have security vulnerabilities. In fact, there have been dozens of patches for a single version of PHP. Usually, your host is responsible for keeping PHP updated; however, many do not take the time to ensure your server is secure by keeping PHP up-to-date. The current version of PHP is 7.0. Any version below 5.6 no longer receives security updates. You can check the version of PHP your server runs using a variety of plugins including my own plugin, My WordPress Health Check. If you discover that you are using an older version, contact your host and ask when it will be updated.</p>\n<h2>MySQL</h2>\n<p>MySQL is the software that powers your WordPress database. Security vulnerabilities in MySQL can allow hackers to get access to the data in your database. Again, your host is usually responsible for keeping MySQL updated but many do not. Any version below 5.5. is not recommended. You can check the version of MySQL your server uses by using a variety of plugins including my own plugin, My WordPress Health Check. If you discover that you are using an older version, contact your host and ask when it will be updated.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/keep-your-software-updated/">Keep your software updated</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:59:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/keep-your-software-updated/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:42:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:39: