tp://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1101:"<p>It has been a while since we released a new update to our newer plugin, My WordPress Health Check. In this new version, we added a new check that looks at the plugins installed on your site and alerts you to if you have a plugin installed that is no longer being supported by the developer. This is a great check to include. There are many times that we find a plugin that fits our need and install it but never go back to ensure that is still being maintained. In fact, when I installed this new update on this site, I was alerted that two of my plugins were no longer being supported. I highly recommend that you install the update and see if you have any plugins installed that are no longer supported.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/my-wp-health-check/">Check out My WordPress Health Check today!</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/new-update-to-my-wordpress-health-check/">New Update To My WordPress Health Check</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:72:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/new-update-to-my-wordpress-health-check/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:42:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:42:"Themes: Finding And Choosing The Right One";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:69:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/themes-finding-and-choosing-the-right-one/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:78:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/themes-finding-and-choosing-the-right-one/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Sun, 17 May 2015 18:35:35 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"WordPress Guides";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:33:"http://mylocalwebstop.com/?p=2190";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:595:"<p>Once you get your website installed and begin working on it, there will come a time when you need to go find your perfect theme. But, where do you look for themes? Additionally, how do you know if the one you find is a good theme? In this guide, we will go over some useful tips and strategies for finding the perfect theme for you site.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/themes-finding-and-choosing-the-right-one/">Themes: Finding And Choosing The Right One</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"Frank";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7424:"<p><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1427" src="http://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/screenshot-current-themes.png" alt="screenshot-current-themes" width="1841" height="535" srcset="https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/screenshot-current-themes.png 1841w, https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/screenshot-current-themes-300x87.png 300w, https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/screenshot-current-themes-1024x298.png 1024w, https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/screenshot-current-themes-600x174.png 600w" sizes="(max-width: 1841px) 100vw, 1841px" />Once you get your website installed and begin working on it, there will come a time when you need to go find your perfect theme. But, where do you look for themes? Additionally, how do you know if the one you find is a good theme? In this guide, we will go over some useful tips and strategies for finding the perfect theme for you site.</p>\n<h3>Where To Find Themes</h3>\n<p>There are hundreds of places that you can go to find WordPress themes. The first place to look is the <a href="https://wordpress.org/themes/" target="_blank">WordPress.org Theme Repository</a>. This repository generally has free themes that have passed community review to ensure that the theme is safe and ready for your site. There are many good themes in the repository and is definitely worth a look. If you decide to look for premium theme, there are many theme marketplaces such as <a href="http://themeforest.net/" target="_blank">Theme Forest</a> and <a href="http://www.templatemonster.com/" target="_blank">Template Monster</a>. Another newer marketplace that you can use to find themes is <a href="https://www.codester.com/" target="_blank">Codester</a>. Alternatively, many theme developers have membership packages for their themes such as <a href="http://www.elegantthemes.com/" target="_blank">Elegant Themes</a>. After these links, the next best place is Google. When you search for themes in Google, you will see thousands of results that you can browse through to find the perfect theme.</p>\n<h3>Deciding On A Theme</h3>\n<p>Once you find a few themes that you like, there are a few things to consider before selecting the theme to install onto your website:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Price</li>\n<li>Speed</li>\n<li>Security</li>\n<li>Design</li>\n<li>Responsiveness</li>\n<li>SEO</li>\n<li>Options/Settings</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Price &#8211; Free vs Premium</h4>\n<p>The most common deciding factor for many users is the price of the theme. However, something to remember is the free is free for a reason. We all like to find a great free theme. However, there are a few reasons that you may want to consider premium themes. First, premium themes usually have better support. Support can range from forums and support tickets to phone and skype support. Premium themes also generally have better documentation and more frequent updates. Premium themes can range from $15 to hundreds.</p>\n<h4>Speed</h4>\n<p>When it comes to finding a theme, a good phrase to remember is &#8220;lean is mean&#8221;. Many themes try to do too much and include too many settings. When themes add in dozens or hundreds of extra features and capabilities, these themes can become slower and bloated. Many of the &#8220;one theme for all sites&#8221; themes are usually loaded with settings that you can customize. However, all these settings add to your site and could potentially slow down your site. Some themes have images, CSS, and JS that isn’t always optimized. Lastly, some themes just aren&#8217;t coded well. So, what can you do to find out? Browse the theme&#8217;s demo to see if you notice any performance issues. A good tip is to go to the Pingdom Website Speed Test and enter the URL of a theme’s demo. This will give you results on speed and performance that may be an indicator to how the theme will perform on your site.</p>\n<h4>Security</h4>\n<p>One of the important things to consider is how secure the theme is. Unfortunately, it is difficult for a non-coder to glance at a theme and know how secure it is. However, there are a few indicators that you can look for to ensure that the developer is keeping the theme secure. First, check to see how frequently the theme is updated. If it is updated regularly, generally, this is a good indicator that the developer is keeping the theme&#8217;s security up to date. Another good indicator to check is the support forums or tickets if they exist. If the developer is fairly active with support, it is a good sign that the developer is actively developing and maintaining the theme. Lastly, check the reviews for the theme if available. Reviewers may mention a security issue that existed or that the developer fixed for them.</p>\n<h4>Design</h4>\n<p>Be sure to browse the demo completely. In most cases, what you see is what you get. If a theme is designed a certain way, changing some details may not be possible or may alter the overall design if changed. So, try to find a theme that is designed very closely to what you are looking for. When browsing the demo, be sure to check pages that you may not consider such as archives, author bio, error pages, and similar pages. You want to make sure these pages are matching the design you are after before you get them on your site and a user notices them.</p>\n<h4>Responsiveness</h4>\n<p>Responsiveness is an important factor in design for today&#8217;s websites. A responsive website adapts when viewed on mobile or smaller devices. Therefore, try to browse the theme&#8217;s demo on a phone or tablet to see how well it looks on those devices. Many search engines now lower your website&#8217;s ranking if your site is not mobile ready or responsive.</p>\n<h4>SEO</h4>\n<p>Themes are not generally considered when improving your SEO but a poorly built theme will be missing certain components to improve your SEO. Check to see if the theme&#8217;s description mentions SEO ready or similar; however, do not always trust the developer completely. A good tip is to is to install an extension or addon for your browser that checks SEO. An example extension for Chrome is <a href="https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/seo-site-tools-site-analy/femogmcmjpjkokoojcljkpfdifkpbbpp?hl=en" target="_blank" class="broken_link">SEO Site Tools</a>.</p>\n<h4>Options/Settings</h4>\n<p>Many themes provide customization settings and options. Unfortunately, you may not be able to see these options browsing the theme but the theme&#8217;s description may provide a screenshot, You want to make sure the features are easy to customize and that the menus and settings pages are easy to navigate and use. You may be using these settings quite frequently so be sure that they menus are logically set up so that you can find the options when you need to.</p>\n<h3>Conclusion</h3>\n<p>Now that you can know where to look and what to look for, go and check out some themes for your site. There are tens of thousands of themes out there, so do not expect to find the perfect theme within minutes. It may take some research to find the theme that matches the design that you are looking for.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/themes-finding-and-choosing-the-right-one/">Themes: Finding And Choosing The Right One</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:74:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/themes-finding-and-choosing-the-right-one/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"2";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:42:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:28:"Developing Your First Plugin";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:56:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/developing-your-first-plugin/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:64:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/developing-your-first-plugin/#respond";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 06 May 2015 20:43:52 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Dev Chat";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:33:"http://mylocalwebstop.com/?p=2159";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:642:"<p>Once you have your WordPress site running, there may come a time when you want to add new functionality to it. Luckily, WordPress has a built in plugin system to allow you to add all kinds of capabilities to your site. But, what if you cannot find the functionality that you are looking for? Maybe, you will start thinking about building your own plugin. Let''s build a simple plugin together to get you started.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/developing-your-first-plugin/">Developing Your First Plugin</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"Frank";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9318:"<p><em>In this series of Dev Chat, I discuss various topics relating to WordPress developers. If you are looking for other topics like this, be sure to check out the other <a href="http://mylocalwebstop.com/category/dev-chat/">Dev Chat</a> articles.</em></p>\n<p>Once you have your WordPress site running, there may come a time when you want to add new functionality to it. Luckily, WordPress has a built in plugin system to allow you to add all kinds of capabilities to your site. But, what if you cannot <a href="http://mylocalwebstop.com/wordpress-basics-finding-using-plugins/" title="WordPress Basics: Finding And Using Plugins">find the functionality</a> that you are looking for? Maybe, you will start thinking about building your own plugin. Let&#8217;s build a simple plugin together to get you started.</p>\n<h2>What Are WordPress Plugins?</h2>\n<p>Instead of changing the code of WordPress itself, you can use a plugin to add the functionality that you seek. A plugin is a set of functions written in PHP that modifies, enhances, or customizes a WordPress site. To do so, we use the WordPress hooks &#8211; <a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Plugin_API#Actions">actions</a> and <a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Plugin_API#Filters">filters</a>. Actions are functions that are executed at certain points in the page load. For example, if you wanted the plugin to do something once the page loads the footer, you would hook your function into the wp_footer action. Filters are functions that replace content from an action. For example, if you wanted to add or replace text in the comments, you could hook your function into the comment_text filter. Don&#8217;t worry about memorizing all the actions and filters to hook into. There are hundreds. For reference, you should bookmark the lists of <a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Plugin_API/Action_Reference">actions</a> and <a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Plugin_API/Filter_Reference">filters</a>.</p>\n<h2>Writing Our Plugin</h2>\n<p>So, now that we understand the concepts of plugins, lets build our first plugin. What we are going to build is a plugin that adds a link to tweet about the post or page at the end of the post or page. So, the first step is to create our PHP file.</p>\n<pre class="prettyprint lang-php"><?php\r\n/**\r\n * Plugin Name: Tweet About Post\r\n * Plugin URI: http://mylocalwebstop.com\r\n * Description: Adds a link to tweet about the post\r\n * Version: 1.0.0\r\n * Author: Frank Corso\r\n * Author URI: http://mylocalwebstop.com\r\n * License: GPL2\r\n */\r\n \r\n ?></pre>\n<p>What you see is the plugin header. This header is always at the beginning of the main file of your plugin and is what tells WordPress that this is a plugin. The <strong>Plugin Name</strong> field is the name of your plugin. The <strong>Plugin URI</strong> is the url to a webpage about your plugin. The <strong>Description</strong> is a short description of the plugin does. The <strong>Version</strong> is the version of your plugin. The <strong>Author </strong>and <strong>Author URI </strong>is about who wrote the plugin and where to find him or her. Lastly, the <strong>License</strong> is used to tell anyone looking at the plugin how it is licensed. Next, it is best practice to follow the header with some information on the license.</p>\n<pre class="prettyprint lang-php">/*  Copyright YEAR  PLUGIN_AUTHOR_NAME  (email : PLUGIN AUTHOR EMAIL)\r\n\r\n    This program is free software; you can redistribute it and/or modify\r\n    it under the terms of the GNU General Public License, version 2, as \r\n    published by the Free Software Foundation.\r\n\r\n    This program is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,\r\n    but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of\r\n    MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the\r\n    GNU General Public License for more details.\r\n\r\n    You should have received a copy of the GNU General Public License\r\n    along with this program; if not, write to the Free Software\r\n    Foundation, Inc., 51 Franklin St, Fifth Floor, Boston, MA  02110-1301  USA\r\n*/</pre>\n<p>Now, we are ready to begin our code. We will be creating a function that hooks into the &#8220;the_content&#8221; filter. So, lets create a function called tweet_the_author and hook it into the filter:</p>\n<pre class="prettyprint lang-php"> \r\n//Our function for this plugin\r\n//WordPress passes into the function the contents that is being filtered\r\nfunction tweet_the_author( $content ) {\r\n\r\n    //We must return the content so WordPress can use it\r\n    return $content;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//Hook it into the filter\r\nadd_filter( ''the_content'', ''tweet_the_author'' );\r\n </pre>\n<p>The function &#8220;add_filter&#8221; is a unique WordPress function that allows us to hook one of our functions into a WordPress filter. So, when WordPress goes to load the content of the post or page, it will run the content through our function. In this case, the content is the page or post the WordPress is loading. When WordPress loads a filter, it passes the content to the filter so we can manipulate it as a parameter. Then, any filter function must return the content so WordPress can then display it. Now that we have our basic function outlined, lets add the tweet link.</p>\n<pre class="prettyprint lang-php"> \r\n//Our function for this plugin\r\n//WordPress passes into the function the contents that is being filtered\r\nfunction tweet_the_author( $content ) {\r\n\r\n    //Retrieves the link to the post\r\n    $post_link = get_permalink();\r\n    \r\n    //Adds anchor to end of content\r\n    $content .= "<a href=''https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=$post_link''>Tweet About This Post!</a>";\r\n    \r\n    //Returns content so WordPress can display it\r\n    return $content;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//Hook it into the filter\r\nadd_filter( ''the_content'', ''tweet_the_author'' );\r\n </pre>\n<p>Now, lets take a look at our completed plugin:</p>\n<pre class="prettyprint lang-php"><?php\r\n/**\r\n * Plugin Name: Tweet About Post\r\n * Plugin URI: http://mylocalwebstop.com\r\n * Description: Adds a link to tweet about the post\r\n * Version: 1.0.0\r\n * Author: Frank Corso\r\n * Author URI: http://mylocalwebstop.com\r\n * License: GPL2\r\n */\r\n \r\n /*  Copyright 2015  Frank Corso  (email : frank@mylocalwebstop.com)\r\n\r\n    This program is free software; you can redistribute it and/or modify\r\n    it under the terms of the GNU General Public License, version 2, as \r\n    published by the Free Software Foundation.\r\n\r\n    This program is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,\r\n    but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of\r\n    MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the\r\n    GNU General Public License for more details.\r\n\r\n    You should have received a copy of the GNU General Public License\r\n    along with this program; if not, write to the Free Software\r\n    Foundation, Inc., 51 Franklin St, Fifth Floor, Boston, MA  02110-1301  USA\r\n*/\r\n\r\n//Our function for this plugin\r\n//WordPress passes into the function the contents that is being filtered\r\nfunction tweet_the_author( $content ) {\r\n\r\n    //Retrieves the link to the post\r\n    $post_link = get_permalink();\r\n    \r\n    //Adds anchor to end of content\r\n    $content .= "<a href=''https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=$post_link''>Tweet About This Post!</a>";\r\n    \r\n    //Returns content so WordPress can display it\r\n    return $content;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//Hook it into the filter\r\nadd_filter( ''the_content'', ''tweet_the_author'' );\r\n\r\n?></pre>\n<p>Now that we have the plugin finished, lets activate it and see what happens.</p>\n<p><img src="http://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/tweet_plugin_example.jpg" alt="tweet_plugin_example" width="697" height="118" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2171" srcset="https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/tweet_plugin_example.jpg 697w, https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/tweet_plugin_example-300x51.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 697px) 100vw, 697px" /></p>\n<p>As you can see, we now have a link at the bottom of the post. If we click on it, it will send us to twitter with the post url in the &#8220;What&#8217;s Happening&#8221; tweet box!</p>\n<h2>Wrap-Up</h2>\n<p>Almost every plugin you make will be built around the WordPress hooks. In our example, we used add_filter to hook into a filter. We can also use add_action to hook into an action. Here are a few resources for getting more familiar with the actions and filers:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Plugin_API/Filter_Reference">Filter Reference</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/add_filter">add_filter Documentation</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Plugin_API/Action_Reference">Action Reference</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/add_action">add_action Documentation</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Now that you have your plugin, be sure to <a href="http://mylocalwebstop.com/writing-your-plugins-readme/" title="Writing Your Plugin’s Readme">create a readme.txt</a> for it too. Be sure to comment below on what plugins that you are making!</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/developing-your-first-plugin/">Developing Your First Plugin</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:61:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/developing-your-first-plugin/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:42:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:30:"Writing Your Plugin’s Readme";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:55:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/writing-your-plugins-readme/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:63:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/writing-your-plugins-readme/#respond";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Tue, 21 Apr 2015 18:45:39 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Dev Chat";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:33:"http://mylocalwebstop.com/?p=2131";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:558:"<p>If you are just getting into WordPress development, then you may be writing your first plugin soon. Plugins are a great way to extend out WordPress. Once you finish, you may decide to release it for others to use through the WordPress repository. But wait! There is something you must first do: write your readme.txt file.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/writing-your-plugins-readme/">Writing Your Plugin&#8217;s Readme</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"Frank";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9436:"<p><em>In this series of Dev Chat, I discuss various topics relating to WordPress developers. If you are looking for other topics like this, be sure to check out the other <a href="http://mylocalwebstop.com/category/dev-chat/">Dev Chat</a> articles.</em></p>\n<p>If you are just getting into WordPress development, then you may be writing your first plugin soon. Plugins are a great way to extend out WordPress. Once you finish, you may decide to release it for others to use through the WordPress repository. But wait! There is something you must first do: write your readme.txt file.</p>\n<h2>What Is The Readme?</h2>\n<p>Your plugin&#8217;s readme has many uses. It creates the description, faq, screenshot, and changelog tabs for your plugin in the repository. For example, almost all the content on the <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/quiz-master-next/">Quiz Master Next repository page</a> is created from the readme file. The readme file also is used to display your plugin information on the Plugins page inside a user&#8217;s WordPress as well. You use the readme to link to your website, help users install your plugin, show off your plugin&#8217;s features, and more. To create the readme, simply create a file called &#8220;readme.txt&#8221; and place it in the root directory of your plugin.</p>\n<h2>Why Should You Care About The Readme?</h2>\n<p>When a user sees a readme file that is written badly, it gives them the impression that the plugin may not be quite up to the standard they need. Or, if the readme isn&#8217;t complete, the user may not even fully understand what the plugin does. A readme that is written well can do many things. By writing a thorough description, users will know exactly what your plugin does and will more likely try it. A well written faq section will help users without having to post in the support forums.</p>\n<h2>The Basic Readme</h2>\n<p>So, lets take a look at an <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/about/readme.txt">example readme from WordPress.org</a>:</p>\n<pre class="prettyprint lang-markdown">=== Plugin Name ===\r\nContributors: (this should be a list of wordpress.org userid''s)\r\nDonate link: http://example.com/\r\nTags: comments, spam\r\nRequires at least: 3.0.1\r\nTested up to: 3.4\r\nStable tag: 4.3\r\nLicense: GPLv2 or later\r\nLicense URI: http://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-2.0.html\r\n\r\nHere is a short description of the plugin.  This should be no more than 150 characters.  No markup here.\r\n\r\n== Description ==\r\n\r\nThis is the long description.  No limit, and you can use Markdown (as well as in the following sections).\r\n\r\nFor backwards compatibility, if this section is missing, the full length of the short description will be used, and\r\nMarkdown parsed.\r\n\r\nA few notes about the sections above:\r\n\r\n*   "Contributors" is a comma separated list of wp.org/wp-plugins.org usernames\r\n*   "Tags" is a comma separated list of tags that apply to the plugin\r\n*   "Requires at least" is the lowest version that the plugin will work on\r\n*   "Tested up to" is the highest version that you''ve *successfully used to test the plugin*. Note that it might work on\r\nhigher versions... this is just the highest one you''ve verified.\r\n*   Stable tag should indicate the Subversion "tag" of the latest stable version, or "trunk," if you use `/trunk/` for\r\nstable.\r\n\r\n    Note that the `readme.txt` of the stable tag is the one that is considered the defining one for the plugin, so\r\nif the `/trunk/readme.txt` file says that the stable tag is `4.3`, then it is `/tags/4.3/readme.txt` that''ll be used\r\nfor displaying information about the plugin.  In this situation, the only thing considered from the trunk `readme.txt`\r\nis the stable tag pointer.  Thus, if you develop in trunk, you can update the trunk `readme.txt` to reflect changes in\r\nyour in-development version, without having that information incorrectly disclosed about the current stable version\r\nthat lacks those changes -- as long as the trunk''s `readme.txt` points to the correct stable tag.\r\n\r\n    If no stable tag is provided, it is assumed that trunk is stable, but you should specify "trunk" if that''s where\r\nyou put the stable version, in order to eliminate any doubt.\r\n\r\n== Installation ==\r\n\r\nThis section describes how to install the plugin and get it working.\r\n\r\ne.g.\r\n\r\n1. Upload `plugin-name.php` to the `/wp-content/plugins/` directory\r\n1. Activate the plugin through the ''Plugins'' menu in WordPress\r\n1. Place `<?php do_action(''plugin_name_hook''); ?>` in your templates\r\n\r\n== Frequently Asked Questions ==\r\n\r\n= A question that someone might have =\r\n\r\nAn answer to that question.\r\n\r\n= What about foo bar? =\r\n\r\nAnswer to foo bar dilemma.\r\n\r\n== Screenshots ==\r\n\r\n1. This screen shot description corresponds to screenshot-1.(png|jpg|jpeg|gif). Note that the screenshot is taken from\r\nthe /assets directory or the directory that contains the stable readme.txt (tags or trunk). Screenshots in the /assets \r\ndirectory take precedence. For example, `/assets/screenshot-1.png` would win over `/tags/4.3/screenshot-1.png` \r\n(or jpg, jpeg, gif).\r\n2. This is the second screen shot\r\n\r\n== Changelog ==\r\n\r\n= 1.0 =\r\n* A change since the previous version.\r\n* Another change.\r\n\r\n= 0.5 =\r\n* List versions from most recent at top to oldest at bottom.\r\n\r\n== Upgrade Notice ==\r\n\r\n= 1.0 =\r\nUpgrade notices describe the reason a user should upgrade.  No more than 300 characters.\r\n\r\n= 0.5 =\r\nThis version fixes a security related bug.  Upgrade immediately.</pre>\n<p>The readme file uses something called Markdown to create the formatting. If you are unfamiliar Markdown, feel free to refer to <a href="http://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/syntax">this well written article</a>. While this readme may look rather self-explanatory, I do have a few tips for improving your readme.</p>\n<h2>The Readme Header</h2>\n<p><img class="aligncenter wp-image-2137 size-full" src="http://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/readme-header.jpg" alt="readme header" width="862" height="172" srcset="https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/readme-header.jpg 862w, https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/readme-header-300x60.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 862px) 100vw, 862px" /></p>\n<p>In the header of your readme, you have a few different fields. The first being the plugin name. Name your plugin something very descriptive of what it does. For example, &#8220;Contact Form 7&#8221; or &#8220;WordPress SEO&#8221; are great names that tell me exactly what they do. Something like &#8220;My Cool Plugin For Your Site&#8221; really doesn&#8217;t tell me much and I probably wouldn&#8217;t look at it.</p>\n<p>The contributors field allows you to link to WordPress.org users. For example, my plugin has fpcorso as the contributor. This will link my profile on WordPress.org to the plugin.</p>\n<p>The tags field are search terms that your plugin falls under. It is a great idea to put several tags here that are relevant to your plugin.</p>\n<h2>The Description</h2>\n<p>You have two different descriptions in the readme. The first line is the short description. This is a small snippet that is placed in smaller areas such as when users are searching for plugins. You want to keep this under 150 characters and to the point. For example, Quiz Master Next&#8217;s short description is &#8220;The easiest and most flexible way to add multiple quizzes, tests, and surveys to your website.&#8221;</p>\n<p>For the main description area, you want to list all the features and capabilities that your plugin has. Some questions to answer in your description include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>What makes it useful?</li>\n<li>Why does the user need your plugin?</li>\n<li>What makes your plugin unique?</li>\n<li>Do you offer any commercial version? List if you have a pro version or addons though be specific about what features are in the free version</li>\n<li>Do you have a website for the plugin?</li>\n<li>Does your plugin have documentation?</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>\n<p>This section is great for anticipating the user&#8217;s questions. A thorough FAQ section will help eliminate some of the topics in the support forums. If I get asked the same question more than once, I usually add it to the FAQ section.</p>\n<h2>Screenshots</h2>\n<p>This is one of the most important sections. Many users will look at your screenshots before or even instead of reading your description. You want to have several screenshots that really show what the plugin does. Include screenshots for the admin area and the front end where relevant.</p>\n<h2>Changelog</h2>\n<p>While this section is rather straight-forward, I always include the date along with each version in the Changelog. Users like to know the frequency of your updates and the time between them. </p>\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\n<p>The readme file is an essential part of every plugin but very few develops use its full potential. Spend some time creating your readme and your plugin&#8217;s user base will grow. Once you finish writing your plugin, it is a good idea to use the<a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/about/validator/"> readme validator</a>. This will tell you if something is wrong with your readme before you upload it.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/writing-your-plugins-readme/">Writing Your Plugin&#8217;s Readme</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:60:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/writing-your-plugins-readme/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:42:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:33:"Learn To Be A WordPress Developer";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:61:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/learn-to-be-a-wordpress-developer/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:69:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/learn-to-be-a-wordpress-developer/#respond";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 09 Apr 2015 03:25:56 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Dev Chat";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:33:"http://mylocalwebstop.com/?p=2114";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:667:"<p>If you have used WordPress for a while, then you may have started thinking about what you would need to learn to become a developer. You could edit your theme or customize your site. You could even create your own custom plugins or themes. But, where do you begin in this journey? There are many ways that you can learn the skills necessary to being a WordPress developer. So, lets take a look at a few of your best resources.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/learn-to-be-a-wordpress-developer/">Learn To Be A WordPress Developer</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"Frank";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4921:"<p><em>In this series of Dev Chat, I discuss various topics relating to WordPress developers. If you are looking for other topics like this, be sure to check out the other <a href="http://mylocalwebstop.com/category/dev-chat/">Dev Chat</a> articles.</em></p>\n<p>If you have used WordPress for a while, then you may have started thinking about what you would need to learn to become a developer. You could edit your theme or customize your site. You could even create your own custom plugins or themes. But, where do you begin in this journey? There are many ways that you can learn the skills necessary to being a WordPress developer. So, lets take a look at a few of your best resources.</p>\n<h2>Learn From The Codex</h2>\n<p><img class="aligncenter wp-image-2115 size-full" src="http://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/codex.png" alt="learn from codex" width="1816" height="945" srcset="https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/codex.png 1816w, https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/codex-300x156.png 300w, https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/codex-1024x533.png 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1816px) 100vw, 1816px" /></p>\n<p>The <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/">WordPress Codex</a> is the official resource for all things relating to WordPress development. There are guides to writing plugins, theme development, and more. Many of the guides link to other articles, tutorials, and resources for further learning. This is a great resource for those looking to learn the WordPress functions and systems who already have a bit of web development experience.</p>\n<h2>Learn Development And WordPress From Treehouse</h2>\n<p><img class="aligncenter wp-image-2118 size-full" src="http://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/treehouse.png" alt="learn with treehouse" width="1601" height="966" srcset="https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/treehouse.png 1601w, https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/treehouse-300x181.png 300w, https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/treehouse-1024x618.png 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1601px) 100vw, 1601px" /></p>\n<p> I have been using Treehouse for quite some time and have been very impressed by the quality of the courses. If you have no web development experience and are looking to learn WordPress development, then this is a great place to start. It will teach you how to program using the front end and php tracks. Then, they even have tracks and courses dedicated to WordPress. I have taken most of their courses and have learned many things from them. Be sure to <a href="http://referrals.trhou.se/frankcorso2">check them out.</a></p>\n<h2>Use The Forums</h2>\n<p>If you are just starting out or have been developing for years, there are two great locations for posting questions. First, the <a href="https://wordpress.org/support/">WordPress Forums</a> are the official support forums for WordPress. There are usually hundreds of people in the forums throughout the day. There have been times that I asked a question and had a response within minutes. Another site is <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/">Stack Overflow</a> which is a great site for people to post questions. Depending on your questions, you could receive dozens of answers from various people.</p>\n<h2>Follow The Top Developers</h2>\n<p>There are dozens of developers who know WordPress better than anyone. These developers have built dozens, if not, hundreds of WordPress sites and have even helped develop the core of WordPress. Finding these developers and keeping up with their Twitter, blog, and projects will help you learn many things. I highly suggest following <a href="https://pippinsplugins.com/">Pippin Williamson</a>, <a href="http://halfelf.org/">Ipstenu</a>, and <a href="https://tommcfarlin.com/">Tom McFarlin</a>.</p>\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\n<p>Now that you have a few resources for learning about WordPress development, go out and build your dream websites. Be sure to leave a comment about your favorite WordPress development resources. Here are a few other resources for your learning journey:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><a href="https://www.webplatform.org/">Web Platform</a> &#8211; Learning HTML, CSS, JavaScript</li>\n<li><a href="http://www.sitepoint.com/">Site Point</a> &#8211; Lots of great tutorials on web development</li>\n<li><a href="http://wp.smashingmagazine.com/">Smashing Magazine</a> &#8211; WordPress news site</li>\n<li><a href="http://wptavern.com/">WP Tavern</a> &#8211; WordPress news site</li>\n<li><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/Learn/Getting_started_with_the_web">MDN</a> &#8211; Getting started with the web guide</li>\n</ol>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/learn-to-be-a-wordpress-developer/">Learn To Be A WordPress Developer</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:66:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/learn-to-be-a-wordpress-developer/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:42:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"Add Documentation To Your Code From The Start";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:73:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/add-documentation-to-your-code-from-the-start/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:81:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/add-documentation-to-your-code-from-the-start/#respond";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 02 Apr 2015 03:09:32 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Dev Chat";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:33:"http://mylocalwebstop.com/?p=2094";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:883:"<p>When I first started developing Quiz Master Next, it was for a personal site of mine that I was adding some quizzes to. I decided to release it as a plugin in case others needed a similar solution. I updated the plugin as I added features on my personal site. But then, users started downloading and using Quiz Master Next in ways that I never thought of and the user base quickly grew. Then, I started getting developers who looked at the code start sending me questions such as "What does this function do?", "Where do you have the function for (random capability)?", or even "Why don''t you have any documentation?".</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/add-documentation-to-your-code-from-the-start/">Add Documentation To Your Code From The Start</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"Frank";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4677:"<p><em>In this series of Dev Chat, I discuss various topics relating to WordPress developers. If you are looking for other topics like this, be sure to check out the other <a href="http://mylocalwebstop.com/category/dev-chat/">Dev Chat</a> articles.</em></p>\n<div style="width: 510px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img title="InvoicePlane Code I by Kovah.de" src="http://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/15330981339_892a2e74e9_php-code.jpg" alt="php documentation photo" width="500" height="351" />\n<p class="wp-caption-text"><small><a style="text-decoration: none;" title="Image inserted by the ImageInject WordPress plugin" href="http://wpinject.com/" rel="nofollow">Photo</a> by <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/50149410@N03/15330981339" target="_blank">Kovah.de</a> <a title="Attribution License" href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow"><img src="http://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-inject/images/cc.png" alt="" /></a></small></p>\n</div>\n<p> When I first started developing Quiz Master Next, it was for a personal site of mine that I was adding some quizzes to. I decided to release it as a plugin in case others needed a similar solution. I updated the plugin as I added features on my personal site. But then, users started downloading and using Quiz Master Next in ways that I never thought of and the user base quickly grew. Then, I started getting developers who looked at the code start sending me questions such as &#8220;What does this function do?&#8221;, &#8220;Where do you have the function for (random capability)?&#8221;, or even &#8220;Why don&#8217;t you have any documentation?&#8221;. Well, since it was originally a personal project, I didn&#8217;t have any documentation. Then, as users quickly asked for more features, the amount of code and files quickly grew. Then, I realized that this is no longer just a personal project and I needed to get some documentation in. By that point, the plugin was thousands of lines of code and dozens of files. If you look at the code now, many things are documented. However, I still have many more things left to create proper code documentation for.</p>\n<h3>Adding Documentation To You Code</h3>\n<p>If you are starting a new project, whether it is a theme, plugin, or even an entire WordPress site, you need to document right from the beginning. Believe me, you do not want to try to adding documentation months down the road. So, how do we document our code in the WordPress ecosystem? There are many styles to documenting your code. Many developers, myself included, follow the <a href="http://www.phpdoc.org/">PHP Doc</a> method for documentation. Lets take a look at an example.</p>\n<pre class="prettyprint lang-php"><?php\r\n/**\r\n  * A summary informing the user what the associated element does.\r\n  *\r\n  * A *description*, that can span multiple lines, to go _in-depth_ into the details of this element\r\n  * and to provide some background information or textual references.\r\n  *\r\n  * @param string $myArgument With a *description* of this argument, these may also\r\n  *    span multiple lines.\r\n  *\r\n  * @return void\r\n  */\r\n  function myFunction($myArgument)\r\n  {\r\n      \r\n  }</pre>\n<p>As you can see, the basic documentation includes a summary, description, a parameter description, and a return description. Most plugin and theme developers also use "since" to show what version of the plugin or theme that a particular function/class was added. Lets take a look at an example of documentation from Quiz Master Next.</p>\n<pre class="prettyprint lang-php"><?php\r\n/**\r\n* Registers Addon Settings Tab\r\n*\r\n* Registers a new tab on the addon settings page\r\n*\r\n* @since 4.0.0\r\n* @param string $title The name of the tab\r\n* @param string $function The function that displays the tab''s content\r\n* @return void\r\n*/</pre>\n<p>As you can see, by adding documentation, a developer looking to customize or extend Quiz Master Next can now easily see what a function does, what the parameters are and what the function returns. Now, since I didn''t document from the beginning, I had to add sections like this to dozens of functions and classes. So, learn from my mistake and document your plugin or theme from the start even if you think you will never release it.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/add-documentation-to-your-code-from-the-start/">Add Documentation To Your Code From The Start</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:78:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/add-documentation-to-your-code-from-the-start/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:45:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:23:"My New Developer Plugin";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:51:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/my-new-developer-plugin/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:59:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/my-new-developer-plugin/#respond";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 02 Mar 2015 00:38:48 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"News";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Our Blog";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:33:"http://mylocalwebstop.com/?p=1742";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:541:"<p>I am thrilled to tell you about my latest plugin. I just released WordPress Developer Toolkit. If you are a WordPress developer, then I suggest that you take a look at it. The plugin will allow you to enter in your plugins and then gives you shortcodes to display information from the WordPress repository such [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/my-new-developer-plugin/">My New Developer Plugin</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"Frank";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:972:"<p>I am thrilled to tell you about my latest plugin. I just released WordPress Developer Toolkit. If you are a WordPress developer, then I suggest that you take a look at it. The plugin will allow you to enter in your plugins and then gives you shortcodes to display information from the WordPress repository such as your amount of downloads, average review, description, and version number. This information gets updated periodically so when you update your plugin, your website will automatically be updated too.</p>\n<p>Be sure to <a class="validating" title="WordPress Developer Toolkit" href="http://mylocalwebstop.com/wordpress-developer-toolkit/" data-cke-saved-href="http://mylocalwebstop.com/wordpress-developer-toolkit/">download the plugin</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/my-new-developer-plugin/">My New Developer Plugin</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:56:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/my-new-developer-plugin/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:45:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:47:"Domains: What Is A Good One And Where To Get It";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:74:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/domains-what-is-a-good-one-and-where-to-get-it/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:82:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/domains-what-is-a-good-one-and-where-to-get-it/#respond";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Sun, 01 Mar 2015 17:46:13 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Our Blog";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"Website Basics";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:33:"http://mylocalwebstop.com/?p=1717";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:518:"<p>So you have just come up with a great idea for a website. Perhaps it is a website for your wedding or maybe it is for your business. What do you do now? Well, the very first step to getting your website online is finding and purchasing a domain name.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/domains-what-is-a-good-one-and-where-to-get-it/">Domains: What Is A Good One And Where To Get It</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"Frank";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6168:"<p><em>In this series of Website Basics, I will be discussing some of the basics to getting your website up. If you are looking for more introductory topics like this, be sure to check out the other <a href="http://mylocalwebstop.com/category/website-basics/">Website Basics</a> articles and my other series, <a href="http://mylocalwebstop.com/category/wordpress-basics/">WordPress Basics</a>.</em></p>\n<p>So you have just come up with a great idea for a website. Perhaps it is a website for your wedding or maybe it is for your business. What do you do now? Well, the very first step to getting your website online is finding and purchasing a domain name.</p>\n<p><span id="more-1717"></span></p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter wp-image-1720 size-full" src="http://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/domain-01.jpg" alt="domain" width="650" height="416" srcset="https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/domain-01.jpg 650w, https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/domain-01-300x192.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px" /></p>\n<h2>What Is A Domain?</h2>\n<p>You may have seen the phrase &#8220;domain name&#8221; but are not quite sure what that might mean. That&#8217;s okay. Think of this website. To get here, you typed in the address bar &#8220;http://www.mylocalwebstop.com&#8221; or something similar. For this website, the domain name is mylocalwebstop.com. Now, what does a domain do? Think of the domain name like your website&#8217;s address. When a user types your url into their browser, the browser is asking the internet where does the website live. The domain name tells the browser where to load the website from.</p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1724" src="http://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/domain-02.png" alt="domain-02" width="581" height="145" srcset="https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/domain-02.png 581w, https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/domain-02-300x75.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 581px) 100vw, 581px" /></p>\n<h2>What Should I Choose For My Domain?</h2>\n<p>When it comes to choosing your domain name, things can get a little tough. Since the internet has been around for 2 decades, a lot of names are already taken. Most names can range from $5 a year to $50 a year. However, if you want a specific name that is already taken, you could be spend thousands. Unless you really need the name, I would suggest looking at a different one. So, what makes a great domain? Here are a few simple guidelines to follow.</p>\n<h4>Keep It Short</h4>\n<p>No one likes having to type in www.theamazingoneofakindwebsitethatisthebestontheinternet.com.  More than likely, most people wouldn&#8217;t even attempt to go to your website. Try to keep the name under 15 letters long.</p>\n<h4>Keep It Simple</h4>\n<p>You may have a short domain name like www.xywkiduwl.com but no one will remember it if you tell them to go to it. Try to stay with simple words or phrases if possible.</p>\n<h4>Keep It Personal</h4>\n<p>Depending on the type of site that you are creating, your options here can vary. If you are creating a site for an event, www.club0001starkeevent.com my not be as appealing as www.littletigersparty.com.</p>\n<h4>Consider Unique Options</h4>\n<p>With domain names, you can have more than just a usual mysite.com. You can have mysite.church, mysite.limo, and even mysite.guru. Be sure to consider some of the newer unique versions when looking for your domain.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>Where Do I Get My Domain?</h2>\n<p>When it comes to places to get your domain, there are literally hundreds of site that you can go to. You want to choose a site that has good support, decent pricing, and easy to use domain management tools. Out of all the sites, there are two that tend to be the most popular.</p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1725" src="http://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/domain-03.png" alt="domain-03" width="901" height="405" srcset="https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/domain-03.png 901w, https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/domain-03-300x135.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 901px) 100vw, 901px" /></p>\n<h4>Hover.com</h4>\n<p>This is one of my favorite companies to use. All of my domains are through them. They offer great support with online chat and a 24/7 support line. Their domain management tools are also very user friendly and easy to use. I highly suggest using them. Be sure to <a href="http://mylocalwebstop.com/go/hover/" class="thirstylink" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" title="check them out">check them out</a>. (Disclaimer: I do receive a small $2 credit if you use that link as I have an account with them. Even if I didn&#8217;t receive credit, I would still recommend them as I have all of my domains through them.)</p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1726" src="http://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/domain-04.png" alt="domain-04" width="1221" height="409" srcset="https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/domain-04.png 1221w, https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/domain-04-300x100.png 300w, https://mylocalwebstop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/domain-04-1024x343.png 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 1221px) 100vw, 1221px" /></p>\n<h4>Godaddy.com</h4>\n<p>Another popular site is godaddy.com. I have several clients that use them and are very satisfied. They have good support and decent pricing. Definitely worth a look. Be sure to <a title="godaddy.com" href="http://godaddy.com" target="_blank">check them out</a>.</p>\n<p>Now that you have chosen a name and purchased it, you have now learned the basics of domain names! Have any questions or use a different domain company? Feel free to leave a comment below.</p>\n<p>What do you want to discuss next? Leave suggestions and ideas in the comments below.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com/domains-what-is-a-good-one-and-where-to-get-it/">Domains: What Is A Good One And Where To Get It</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://mylocalwebstop.com">My Local Webstop</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:79:"https://mylocalwebstop.com/domains-what-is-a-good-one-and-where-to-get-it/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a: